{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.86,0.02,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1130"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"646"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department shortly after insertion of a right subclavian venous line for chemotherapy administration. She has become increasingly breathless and has difficulty speaking. Her blood pressure has fallen from 126/72 mmHg to 74/44 mmHg. Her pulse rate is 120/min, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her trachea is deviated to the left and no breath sounds can be heard over the right side of her chest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endotracheal intubation","Needle thoracostomy","1L of intravenous fluid","15L of oxygen via non-rebreather mask","Urgent computed tomography pulmonary angiogram"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe increasing breathlessness, hypotension, tracheal deviation and absent breath sounds are diagnostic of a tension pneumothorax, likely caused by subclavian line insertion. This is a clinical diagnosis requiring immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA tension pneumothorax is treated with emergency decompression. This is first attempted with a\u003Cstrong\u003E needle thoracostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the emergency first-line treatment for tension pneumothorax. This is performed in the 2nd intercostal space, mid-clavicular line generally. Whilst a venipuncture needle may be the closest cannula on hand in such situations, such an approach may not always gain access to the pleural cavity. There may too much tissue on the anterior chest wall in the well-muscled or obese patient and in such cases, if a longer catheter is not available, an approach through the fifth intercostal space in the mid-axillary line may be more practical. If the patient had an uncomplicated pneumothorax, then a tube thoracostomy would be appropriate. However, the patient has acute shortness of breath, hypotension and a mediastinal shift - immediate needle decompression is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E with positive pressure ventilation would be dangerous in tension pneumothorax as it would likely worsen the condition by increasing intrathoracic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile this patient is hypotensive, \u003Cstrong\u003E1L of intravenous fluid\u003C/strong\u003E will not address the underlying obstructive shock caused by the tension pneumothorax. The priority is to decompress the chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough supplemental \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen via a non-rebreather mask\u003C/strong\u003E may temporarily improve oxygenation, it does not address the life-threatening tension component which requires immediate decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArranging a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomputed tomography pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would delay life-saving treatment. While pulmonary embolism can present similarly, the temporal relationship to line insertion and classical signs of tension pneumothorax make the diagnosis clear without need for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A tension pneumothorax is a clinical diagnosis requiring immediate needle thoracostomy without waiting for imaging.","Tension pneumothorax presents with respiratory distress, hypotension, tracheal deviation, and absent breath sounds on the affected side.","Needle thoracostomy is performed in the 2nd intercostal space, mid-clavicular line or 5th intercostal space, mid-axillary line."],"references":["Jalota R, Sayad E. Tension Pneumothorax. [Updated 2021 Jan 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559090/","Martin M, Satterly S, Inaba K, Blair K. Does needle thoracostomy provide adequate and effective decompression of tension pneumothorax? J Trauma Acute Care Surg. 2012 Dec;73(6):1412-7. doi: 10.1097/TA.0b013e31825ac511. PMID: 22902737.","DeMaio A, Semaan R. Management of Pneumothorax. Clin Chest Med. 2021 Dec;42(4):729-738. doi: 10.1016/j.ccm.2021.08.008. PMID: 34774178."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61740"}},"question":{"data":{"typ